export const story = {"seriesId":"the-friend-in-the-frame","storyId":"the-friend-in-the-frame","storyKey":"the-friend-in-the-frame/the-friend-in-the-frame","seriesTitle":"The Friend in the Frame","seriesDescription":"Benjamin's imaginary friend Fig has been his best friend since he was five. But when Fig starts showing up in family photos—and then in OLD photos from before Benjamin was born—things get weird. The mystery is never solved. But some things don't need explaining.","title":"The Friend in the Frame","author":"Benjamin & Fig","description":"Benjamin's imaginary friend Fig has been his best friend since he was five. But when Fig starts showing up in family photos—and then in OLD photos from before Benjamin was born—things get weird. The mystery is never solved. But some things don't need explaining.","ageRange":"7-10","genre":"Magical Realism","tags":["friendship","family","imagination","mystery","heartwarming"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"My Best Friend Fig","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# My Best Friend Fig\n\nI met Fig when I was five years old.\n\nIt was the summer we moved to the new house, the one with the big backyard and the creaky stairs. Mom and Dad were busy unpacking boxes, and I was sitting on the porch, watching ants carry crumbs across the wood.\n\n\"Those ants are working really hard,\" said a voice next to me.\n\nI looked up. There was a kid sitting there—about my age, with messy brown hair and a striped shirt that looked like it was from a long time ago. The kind of shirt you see in old photographs.\n\n\"I'm Fig,\" the kid said. \"Want to be friends?\"\n\nI did want to be friends. I wanted it more than anything.\n\nSo I said yes.\n\n---\n\nHere's the thing about being an only child: it's quiet.\n\nMy parents love me. I know they do. But Dad works late most nights, and Mom has her phone pressed to her ear so often that I sometimes forget what her voice sounds like when it's not saying \"Sorry, can you hold on one second?\"\n\nFig doesn't have a phone. Fig doesn't have anywhere else to be.\n\nWhen I come home from school, Fig is waiting in my room. When I can't sleep, Fig tells me stories about a place called the In-Between, which sounds made up but also sounds kind of real. When I eat dinner alone because Mom's on a conference call and Dad's still at the office, Fig sits across from me and asks about my day.\n\n\"Tell me everything,\" Fig says. \"I want to know everything.\"\n\nSo I tell Fig everything. And Fig listens like it matters.\n\n---\n\nMy parents don't see Fig.\n\nI figured this out pretty early. When I was six, I asked Mom to set an extra place at dinner for Fig, and she laughed and said, \"Of course, sweetie,\" in that voice adults use when they're not really listening. She put out a plate, but she kept glancing at her phone.\n\n\"She can't see me,\" Fig said quietly. \"It's okay. I'm used to it.\"\n\n\"Used to it?\"\n\nFig just shrugged. \"Some people can see me. Most people can't. You can. That's what matters.\"\n\nI stopped asking for extra plates after that. But I always saved Fig half my dessert. Just in case.\n\n---\n\nThe first photograph happened on my ninth birthday.\n\nIt was a small party—just me, Mom, Dad, and a cake from the grocery store. Dad set up his phone on a tripod (he's very into photography \"as a hobby,\" which mostly means he takes blurry pictures of birds).\n\n\"Okay, everyone squeeze in!\" Dad said.\n\nMom put her arm around me. I smiled. Fig stood behind us, near the window, waving at the camera.\n\n\"Can Fig be in the picture too?\" I asked.\n\nMom's smile flickered. \"Sure, honey. Fig can be in the picture.\"\n\nShe didn't look at the window. She didn't see Fig waving.\n\nDad clicked the button. The phone flashed. And that was that.\n\nLater that night, after cake and presents and the awkward silence when my parents ran out of birthday conversation, I looked at the photo on Dad's phone.\n\nThere we were—Mom, Dad, and me, squished together in front of my cake.\n\nAnd behind us, near the window, was a blur.\n\nA blur shaped like a person.\n\n\"Dad?\" I said. \"What's that?\"\n\nHe squinted at the screen. \"Huh. Must be a smudge on the lens. Or maybe the light was weird.\" He swiped to the next photo, a blurry picture of a sparrow. \"Don't worry about it.\"\n\nBut I did worry about it.\n\nBecause the blur had messy brown hair. And I could almost—*almost*—see stripes.\n\n---\n\nThat night, Fig sat on the edge of my bed while I stared at the ceiling.\n\n\"Fig?\"\n\n\"Yeah?\"\n\n\"Were you trying to be in the picture?\"\n\nFig was quiet for a long moment. When I looked over, Fig's face was strange. Hopeful and scared at the same time.\n\n\"I just wanted to be part of it,\" Fig said. \"Part of the family. Is that... is that okay?\"\n\nI didn't know what to say.\n\nSo I just said, \"Yeah. That's okay.\"\n\nFig smiled—the real kind of smile, the kind that takes over your whole face.\n\n\"I'll try harder next time,\" Fig said. \"Maybe they'll see me. Maybe they'll all see me.\"\n\nI didn't know if that was a good thing or a scary thing.\n\nBut Fig looked so happy that I didn't have the heart to say anything else.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"The Blur Gets Clearer","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# The Blur Gets Clearer\n\nOver the next few weeks, Fig started showing up everywhere.\n\nNot in real life—Fig was always there in real life. I mean in pictures.\n\nFirst it was the photo Dad took of me doing homework. I was at the kitchen table, frowning at a math worksheet. Behind me, near the refrigerator, there was a blur.\n\n\"Lens flare,\" Dad said.\n\nThen it was the picture Mom took for Grandma, the one of me in my new winter coat. I was standing by the front door, smiling the kind of smile you make when someone tells you to smile. And in the mirror behind me, there was a shape. A kid-shaped shape.\n\n\"Weird reflection,\" Mom said.\n\nThen it was the selfie I took with Mom at the park. We were on a bench, leaves falling around us. And between us, squeezed into the frame like they'd been there all along, was a face.\n\nNot a blur this time. A *face*. Messy brown hair. A nervous smile.\n\nFig.\n\n\"Mom,\" I said, \"do you see that?\"\n\nShe looked at the photo. Her eyebrows went together the way they do when she's confused.\n\n\"See what, honey?\"\n\n\"Between us. There's—\" I pointed at the screen. \"Right there. That's Fig.\"\n\nMom was quiet for a long moment. Then she laughed, but it wasn't a funny laugh.\n\n\"That's just... that's a glitch, Benjamin. Phones do weird things sometimes.\"\n\nShe deleted the photo.\n\n---\n\nThat night, Fig sat in my desk chair, spinning slowly.\n\n\"She deleted it,\" I said.\n\n\"I know.\"\n\n\"You were RIGHT THERE. Your face was right there.\"\n\nFig stopped spinning. \"Did I look okay?\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"In the picture.\" Fig looked embarrassed. \"Did I look okay? I've never been in a picture before. I didn't know if I was doing it right.\"\n\nI didn't know what to say. Fig was worried about their *angle*.\n\n\"You looked fine,\" I said. \"You looked... real.\"\n\nFig smiled. That big, whole-face smile.\n\n\"I felt real,\" Fig said. \"For just a second, when the camera clicked, I felt really, really real.\"\n\n---\n\nThe pictures kept coming.\n\nAt my cousin's wedding, Fig appeared in the background of seventeen different photos. Tiny at first—just a blur behind the cake table—but getting clearer each time. By the last photo of the night, you could see the stripes on Fig's shirt.\n\nAt Thanksgiving, Fig was in the family portrait. Standing right next to me, clear as day, while everyone else smiled at the camera.\n\nMy uncle posted it on Facebook. Nobody commented on the extra kid.\n\n\"Why can't they see it?\" I asked Fig later. \"It's so obvious. You're RIGHT THERE.\"\n\nFig shrugged. \"Maybe they don't want to see it. Grown-ups are like that sometimes. They only see what makes sense.\"\n\n---\n\nBut then Mom found the birthday photos.\n\nIt was a Sunday afternoon. She was cleaning out the junk drawer, and she found the stack of printed photos from my party—the ones Grandma had insisted on printing because \"phones break, but photographs last forever.\"\n\nI was in my room when I heard her gasp.\n\nThen: \"David? DAVID. Come look at this.\"\n\nI crept to the top of the stairs. My parents were in the kitchen, hunched over the photos, flipping through them one by one.\n\n\"This one too,\" Dad said. \"And this one. And—oh. Oh, that's...\"\n\n\"Who IS that?\" Mom's voice was shaking. \"That's not a smudge. That's not a lens flare. That's a CHILD.\"\n\nI looked at Fig. Fig looked at me.\n\n\"They can see me,\" Fig whispered. \"Benjamin. They can *see* me.\"\n\nFig looked terrified.\n\nAnd honestly? So was I.\n\n---\n\nThat night, my parents sat me down at the kitchen table. The photos were spread out in front of us like evidence.\n\n\"Benjamin,\" Dad said carefully. \"Is there something you want to tell us?\"\n\nI looked at the photos. At Fig's face, getting clearer and clearer with each one. At Fig's hopeful, scared expression.\n\nAnd then I looked at the corner of the kitchen, where Fig stood, invisible to my parents, watching with wide eyes.\n\n\"That's Fig,\" I said. \"My friend. I've been telling you about Fig for years.\"\n\nMom and Dad exchanged a look.\n\n\"Fig is... imaginary, sweetheart,\" Mom said gently.\n\n\"Then how is Fig in the pictures?\"\n\nNeither of them had an answer for that.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Old Albums","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# The Old Albums\n\nMom became obsessed with the photos.\n\nShe dug out every album we had—the dusty ones from the closet, the boxes from the garage, the folders on her computer labeled \"Backup DO NOT DELETE.\" She spread them across the dining room table and went through them one by one, like a detective looking for clues.\n\n\"What are you doing?\" I asked, standing in the doorway.\n\n\"Looking,\" she said without looking up. \"If this... if there's really something in the pictures, I want to know when it started.\"\n\n\"It started at my birthday,\" I said. \"I told you.\"\n\nBut she wasn't listening. She was flipping through photos from last Christmas. Then from the summer. Then from the school year before that.\n\nI watched her face change.\n\n\"David?\" she called. Her voice was strange. \"David, come here.\"\n\n---\n\nThe photos were spread out in a line.\n\nEach one had Fig in it.\n\nNot in the background anymore—in the *middle*. Standing next to me at the school play. Sitting beside me at the breakfast table. Peeking over my shoulder while I opened presents.\n\n\"These are from two years ago,\" Dad said slowly. \"This is from... this is from when you were seven.\"\n\n\"Fig has been my friend since I was five,\" I said.\n\nMom and Dad looked at each other.\n\n\"Okay,\" Mom said. \"Okay. That's... that doesn't make sense, but okay. Let's keep looking.\"\n\nShe pulled out an older album. The one with the faded cover and the yellow pages.\n\nBaby pictures. My first steps. The day they brought me home from the hospital.\n\nMom flipped through the pages. I watched her hands shake.\n\nAnd then she stopped.\n\nThere, in a photo of me as a baby—tiny, red-faced, wrapped in a blanket in my mother's arms—was a blur near the window.\n\nA blur shaped like a kid.\n\n\"That's not possible,\" Dad whispered. \"Benjamin was a NEWBORN. He didn't have an imaginary friend when he was a newborn.\"\n\nMom kept flipping. Her hands moved faster now.\n\nMy first birthday. Fig in the background, blurry.\n\nMy second birthday. Fig a little clearer.\n\nMy third birthday. Fig standing right next to me, both of us reaching for the candles.\n\n\"I don't understand,\" Mom said. \"I don't—how is this—\"\n\nShe flipped back further. To photos from before I was born.\n\nThe photo of Mom and Dad at their anniversary dinner, a year before I existed. And in the corner of the restaurant, sitting alone at a table, was a kid with messy brown hair and a striped shirt.\n\nWaiting.\n\n---\n\n\"Fig,\" I said that night. \"What ARE you?\"\n\nFig was sitting on my bed, knees pulled up to their chest. Fig looked smaller than usual. Scared.\n\n\"I don't know,\" Fig said. \"I really don't know.\"\n\n\"You're in photos from before I was born. You were there before I even existed.\"\n\n\"I was waiting.\" Fig's voice was barely a whisper. \"I was waiting for someone who could see me. And then you came, and you SAW me, and I wasn't alone anymore.\"\n\n\"But how long were you waiting?\"\n\nFig didn't answer.\n\n\"Fig. How long?\"\n\n\"A long time.\" Fig's eyes were shiny, like they were about to cry. \"A really, really long time, Benjamin. I don't know how long. I don't remember when it started. I just remember being alone. And then I remember you.\"\n\nI didn't know what to say. So I did what Fig always did for me when I didn't have words.\n\nI listened.\n\n\"I just wanted to be real,\" Fig said. \"I wanted to be part of something. Part of a family. I didn't mean to scare anyone. I didn't mean to show up in the photos. I just wanted it so badly that it... happened.\"\n\n\"You wanted to be seen.\"\n\n\"I wanted to MATTER.\" Fig looked at me. \"You're the only person who ever made me feel like I mattered. And I thought maybe, if I could be in the pictures, I could matter to your parents too. I could be part of your family. Not just your imaginary friend.\"\n\nThe words hit me somewhere deep.\n\n\"You're not imaginary to me,\" I said. \"You never were.\"\n\nFig smiled. A small, sad smile.\n\n\"I know,\" Fig said. \"That's why I picked you.\"\n\n---\n\nDownstairs, I could hear my parents arguing.\n\n\"We need to take him to someone,\" Mom was saying. \"A doctor. A therapist. Something.\"\n\n\"And tell them what? That there's a ghost in our photos?\"\n\n\"It's not a ghost. It's—I don't know what it is. But something is wrong.\"\n\nI looked at Fig.\n\nSomething is wrong, Mom said.\n\nBut looking at Fig—at my best friend, my only real friend, the person who'd been there for me when no one else was—nothing felt wrong at all.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Everyone Thinks I'm Crazy","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Everyone Thinks I'm Crazy\n\nDr. Reyes had a nice office.\n\nThere were plants on the windowsill and a bowl of candy on her desk. The chairs were soft and squishy. On the wall was a poster of a cat hanging from a branch that said \"Hang In There!\"\n\nFig looked at the poster and said, \"That cat seems stressed.\"\n\nI tried not to laugh. Dr. Reyes noticed.\n\n\"Something funny, Benjamin?\"\n\n\"No. Sorry.\"\n\nShe smiled. She had a kind smile, the kind that made you want to trust her. But I didn't trust her. I didn't trust anyone my parents had called \"a professional who can help.\"\n\n\"Your parents told me you have a friend named Fig,\" Dr. Reyes said. \"Can you tell me about Fig?\"\n\nI looked at Fig, who was sitting in the chair next to me. Fig gave me a small nod.\n\n\"Fig is my best friend,\" I said. \"We met when I was five.\"\n\n\"And what does Fig look like?\"\n\n\"Brown hair. Messy. A striped shirt. About my age.\"\n\nDr. Reyes wrote something down. \"And where is Fig right now?\"\n\nI pointed to the chair next to me. \"Right there.\"\n\nDr. Reyes looked at the empty chair. She looked at me. She wrote something else down.\n\n\"Benjamin,\" she said gently, \"do you know what an imaginary friend is?\"\n\n\"Fig isn't imaginary.\"\n\n\"I understand it feels that way. But sometimes, when children feel lonely, they create friends in their minds. It's very normal. It's actually a sign of creativity and intelligence.\"\n\n\"Then why is Fig in the photos?\"\n\nDr. Reyes paused. \"What do you mean?\"\n\n\"The photos. Fig is in all of them. My mom can show you. Fig is in pictures from before I was born.\"\n\nDr. Reyes's smile stayed the same, but something behind her eyes shifted.\n\n\"Benjamin, that's not possible. Photographs capture reality. If your friend isn't real—\"\n\n\"Fig IS real.\" I stood up. I didn't mean to, but I was angry. \"I'm not crazy. I'm not making things up. Fig is sitting RIGHT THERE and just because you can't see them doesn't mean they don't exist!\"\n\nThe room went quiet.\n\nFig was looking at me with wide eyes. Nobody had ever stood up for Fig before. Not like that.\n\nDr. Reyes put down her pen.\n\n\"I believe that YOU believe Fig is real,\" she said carefully. \"And we can talk about why that is. But Benjamin, there's no one in that chair. There's no one in your photographs. Whatever you're seeing... we need to figure out what's happening.\"\n\nI looked at Fig.\n\nFig was crying. Quiet tears, rolling down their cheeks.\n\n\"She can't see me,\" Fig whispered. \"No matter how hard I try. She can't see me.\"\n\nAnd that's when I realized: this wasn't about proving Fig was real. Dr. Reyes would never believe me. My parents would never believe me. The whole world would look at that empty chair and see nothing.\n\nBut I saw Fig. I ALWAYS saw Fig.\n\nAnd that had to be enough.\n\n---\n\nThe car ride home was silent.\n\nMom kept glancing at me in the rearview mirror. Dad stared straight ahead.\n\n\"Dr. Reyes thinks we should try some new strategies,\" Mom said finally. \"She thinks if we stop... encouraging the behavior... Fig might fade away on their own.\"\n\n\"Fig isn't a behavior,\" I said.\n\n\"Benjamin—\"\n\n\"Fig is my FRIEND. My only real friend. The only person who actually listens to me, who actually SEES me, who doesn't just nod and say 'that's nice, honey' while looking at their phone.\"\n\nThe car got very quiet.\n\nMom's hands tightened on the steering wheel.\n\n\"That's not fair,\" she said, but her voice was shaky.\n\n\"Isn't it?\"\n\nWe drove the rest of the way in silence.\n\n---\n\nThat night, Fig sat at the end of my bed.\n\n\"I'm sorry,\" Fig said. \"This is all my fault. If I hadn't shown up in the photos, none of this would be happening. Your parents wouldn't be scared. You wouldn't be in trouble.\"\n\n\"You didn't do anything wrong.\"\n\n\"I made things harder for you.\"\n\n\"No.\" I sat up. \"You made things better. You've ALWAYS made things better. And I'm not going to let them make you disappear.\"\n\nFig looked at me. \"What are you going to do?\"\n\nI thought about it. About Dr. Reyes and her empty-chair theory. About my parents and their fear. About Fig, who had waited so long, SO long, just to be seen.\n\n\"I'm going to tell them the truth,\" I said. \"Not about whether you're real or imaginary. About what you mean to me. About why I need you.\"\n\n\"And if they don't listen?\"\n\nI looked at my best friend—my impossible, unexplainable, absolutely-real-to-me best friend.\n\n\"Then I'll make them listen,\" I said. \"Because that's what friends do.\"\n\nFig smiled. The whole-face smile.\n\nFor the first time in days, so did I.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"The Conversation","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# The Conversation\n\nI found my parents in the kitchen, sitting at the table with the photos spread out between them.\n\nThey weren't arguing anymore. They weren't even talking. They were just staring at the pictures like they might reveal their secrets if they looked long enough.\n\n\"Can I talk to you?\" I said.\n\nThey looked up. Mom's eyes were red. Dad looked tired.\n\n\"Of course, buddy,\" Dad said. \"Come sit.\"\n\nI pulled up a chair. Took a breath.\n\n\"I know you think I'm making Fig up,\" I said. \"I know Dr. Reyes thinks I'm lonely and creative and that this is some kind of coping thing. And maybe you're right. Maybe I AM lonely. Maybe I DO need someone to talk to.\"\n\nMom reached across the table like she wanted to take my hand. I let her.\n\n\"But here's the thing,\" I continued. \"Fig has been there for me when nobody else was. When you're at work and I come home to an empty house, Fig is there. When I can't sleep because the house is too quiet, Fig tells me stories. When I eat dinner alone, Fig sits with me.\"\n\nMom's hand tightened on mine.\n\n\"I'm not saying it's your fault,\" I said quickly. \"I know you have to work. I know you love me. But I need you to understand—Fig isn't a problem. Fig isn't something that needs to be fixed. Fig is my FRIEND. The best friend I've ever had.\"\n\nThe kitchen was quiet.\n\n\"And I don't know why Fig is in the photos,\" I said. \"I don't know how it's possible. Maybe it's magic. Maybe it's science. Maybe it's something nobody will ever be able to explain. But instead of trying to make it go away, maybe you could just... accept it? Accept that I have a friend you can't see, and that's okay?\"\n\nDad rubbed his eyes. Mom was crying again—but differently this time. Not scared crying. Something else.\n\n\"Benjamin,\" Dad said slowly, \"what you said about being lonely... we had no idea.\"\n\n\"We've been so busy,\" Mom said. \"With work, with everything. We didn't realize—\" She stopped. Took a breath. \"We didn't realize you needed us and we weren't there.\"\n\n\"Fig was there,\" I said. \"Fig is always there.\"\n\nMom looked at the photos. Really looked at them, for the first time.\n\n\"This one,\" she said softly. She pointed at a picture from Christmas. \"Look at... at the expression on the face. Whoever—whatever this is—they look...\"\n\n\"Hopeful,\" Dad said.\n\n\"Hopeful,\" Mom agreed. \"Like they're waiting to be noticed.\"\n\nShe flipped to another photo. My seventh birthday. Fig standing next to me, almost touching my shoulder but not quite.\n\n\"And this one. They look nervous. Like they're not sure if they belong.\"\n\nShe looked up at me.\n\n\"Benjamin... is that how Fig feels? Like they don't belong?\"\n\nI thought about Fig. About the striped shirt from another time. About the In-Between. About waiting for years and years just for someone who could see you.\n\n\"Fig just wants to be part of a family,\" I said. \"Fig has been alone for a really long time.\"\n\nMom was quiet for a long moment.\n\nThen she did something I didn't expect.\n\nShe picked up one of the photos—the one from my birthday, where Fig's face was clearest—and she looked right at it.\n\n\"Hi, Fig,\" she said. \"I'm Sarah. Benjamin's mom.\"\n\nDad stared at her. I stared at her.\n\n\"I can't see you,\" Mom continued, still looking at the photo. \"I don't understand any of this. But my son loves you, and you've been there for him when I wasn't. So... thank you. And if you want to be part of this family...\" She swallowed. \"Then I guess you're part of this family.\"\n\nFrom the doorway, invisible to everyone but me, Fig made a sound like a sob.\n\n\"She's talking to me,\" Fig whispered. \"Benjamin. She's TALKING to me.\"\n\nI smiled.\n\n\"Yeah,\" I said. \"She is.\"\n\nDad looked at Mom like she'd lost her mind. Then he looked at the photo. Then at me.\n\n\"I'm not saying I believe in ghosts,\" he said slowly. \"But I'm also not saying I DON'T believe. Because I've looked at these photos a hundred times, and I can't explain what I'm seeing. And if you say Fig is real...\" He sighed. \"Then I'm going to trust you, buddy. I'm going to trust that you see something we can't.\"\n\n\"Thank you,\" I said.\n\n\"So.\" Dad drummed his fingers on the table. \"What does Fig like for breakfast? Because if they're part of this family, they're eating at the table with us.\"\n\nI laughed. The first real laugh in weeks.\n\nAnd from the doorway, Fig laughed too.\n","narration":null},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"Family Portrait","file":"chapter-6.md","markdown":"# Family Portrait\n\nFig eats pancakes.\n\nI didn't know imaginary friends could eat, but apparently they can—or at least, Fig can. Every morning, Mom sets out four plates instead of three. Four glasses of orange juice. Four napkins.\n\n\"More syrup, Fig?\" she asks, holding the bottle toward the empty-looking chair.\n\nI pass the syrup.\n\n\"Fig says thank you,\" I report.\n\n\"You're welcome, Fig,\" Mom says.\n\nDad still looks slightly uncomfortable with all of this. But he's trying. Yesterday he asked Fig about the weather, and when I translated Fig's answer (\"Fig says it feels like a 'between day'—not warm, not cold, just in-between\"), Dad nodded seriously and said, \"I know exactly what you mean, Fig.\"\n\nHe doesn't know what Fig means. But he's trying, and that matters.\n\n---\n\nThings are different now.\n\nMom works from home two days a week. Dad comes home earlier. We eat dinner together—all four of us—almost every night.\n\n\"How was school?\" Dad asks.\n\n\"Fine,\" I say. \"We had a spelling test.\"\n\n\"How'd you do?\"\n\n\"I got a ninety-two. I missed 'necessary.'\"\n\n\"That's a hard one,\" Mom says. \"How about you, Fig? How was your day?\"\n\nI look at Fig, who is beaming.\n\n\"Fig says they reorganized my bookshelf by color,\" I translate. \"And they found a quarter under my bed.\"\n\n\"Very productive,\" Dad says. \"Good work, Fig.\"\n\nFig doesn't stop smiling for the rest of dinner.\n\n---\n\nWe never figured out what Fig is.\n\nNot a ghost, exactly—ghosts are supposed to be dead people, and Fig doesn't remember ever being alive. Not a hallucination—hallucinations don't show up in photographs. Not a spirit or a demon or an angel or any of the things Dad quietly Googled late at night when he thought I wasn't watching.\n\nFig is just... Fig.\n\nSomething that exists in the In-Between. Something that waited a long, long time to find a friend. Something that wanted so badly to be real that it started to become real, one photograph at a time.\n\nWe don't understand it.\n\nBut we've stopped trying to understand it.\n\nSome things just are.\n\n---\n\nThe holiday card this year has four people in it.\n\nMom, Dad, me, and Fig.\n\nWe took the picture in front of the fireplace. Dad set up the tripod. Mom wore her red sweater. I wore the uncomfortable collared shirt I only wear for pictures.\n\nAnd Fig stood right next to me, arm around my shoulder, grinning at the camera.\n\n\"Everyone say 'cheese'!\" Dad said.\n\n\"Cheese!\" said Mom and me.\n\n\"Cheese!\" said Fig, even though no one else could hear it.\n\nThe camera flashed.\n\nAnd when we looked at the photo—really looked at it—there was Fig. Clear as day. Part of the family.\n\nMom started to cry again. The happy kind this time.\n\n\"We should send this to Grandma,\" she said.\n\n\"Grandma's going to have questions,\" Dad pointed out.\n\n\"Grandma's going to have to deal with it,\" Mom said. \"Fig is family now.\"\n\n---\n\nThat night, after the cards were addressed and the dishes were washed and the house was quiet, Fig sat with me on the porch.\n\nIt was cold outside, but not too cold. A between kind of night.\n\n\"Thank you,\" Fig said.\n\n\"For what?\"\n\n\"For not giving up on me.\" Fig looked at the stars. \"Everyone else did. Everyone else looked right through me. But you saw me. And you fought for me. And now...\"\n\nFig gestured at the house behind us. At the warmth through the windows. At the stack of holiday cards with four faces instead of three.\n\n\"Now I'm part of something,\" Fig finished.\n\nI leaned my head against Fig's shoulder. Fig felt solid and real and there.\n\n\"You always were,\" I said. \"You just didn't know it yet.\"\n\nWe sat there for a while, watching our breath fog in the cold air.\n\nTwo breaths. Side by side.\n\nBoth real.\n\nBoth here.\n\n---\n\n*Nobody ever figured out what Fig was.*\n\n*The mystery stayed a mystery.*\n\n*But that was okay.*\n\n*Because Fig was family now.*\n\n*And family doesn't need an explanation.*\n\n*Family just needs a place at the table.*\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":6,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
